Covid 19 Epidemionlogy with R

Rf.:

  • the following analysis is based on this post
  • You can find Modelling the effects of public health interventions on COVID-19 transmission using R - part 1 in details
  • also the R Epidemics Consortium will provide you the tool

Getting data

We are now getting data from JHU data gathered since beginning of the COVID-19. The address below contains the data live. We are going to subset it to Canada.

```r
jhu_url <- paste(\https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/\, 
  \COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/\, \csse_covid_19_time_series/\, 
  \time_series_19-covid-Confirmed.csv\, sep = \\)
jhu_url

```r
```r
library(lubridate)
library(incidence)

ca_confirmed_long_jhu <- read_csv(jhu_url) %>% 
  rename(province = \Province/State\, 
  country_region = \Country/Region\) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-c(province, country_region, Lat, Long), 
               names_to = \Date\, 
               values_to = \cumulative_cases\) %>% 
  # adjust JHU dates back one day to reflect US time, more or less
  mutate(Date = mdy(Date) - days(1)) %>% 
  filter(country_region == \Canada\) %>% 
  arrange(province, Date) %>% 
  group_by(province) %>% 
  mutate(
    incident_cases = c(0, diff(cumulative_cases))
    ) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(-country_region, -Lat, -Long) %>% 
  filter(str_detect(province, \Diamond Princess\, negate = TRUE))

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

### Calculate at country level

So calculate the cumulative and incident cases at group level:



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2FfY29uZmlybWVkIDwtIGNhX2NvbmZpcm1lZF9sb25nX2podSAlPiVcbiAgZ3JvdXBfYnkoRGF0ZSkgJT4lXG4gIHN1bW1hcmlzZShcbiAgICBjdW11bGF0aXZlX2Nhc2VzID0gc3VtKGN1bXVsYXRpdmVfY2FzZXMpLFxuICAgIGluY2lkZW50X2Nhc2VzID0gc3VtKGluY2lkZW50X2Nhc2VzKVxuICApXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
ca_confirmed <- ca_confirmed_long_jhu %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  summarise(
    cumulative_cases = sum(cumulative_cases),
    incident_cases = sum(incident_cases)
  )

### A quick fit exponential models to incidence data


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2FfY29uZmlybWVkIDwtIGNhX2NvbmZpcm1lZF9sb25nX2podSAlPiVcbiAgZ3JvdXBfYnkoRGF0ZSkgJT4lXG4gIHN1bW1hcmlzZShcbiAgICBjdW11bGF0aXZlX2Nhc2VzID0gc3VtKGN1bXVsYXRpdmVfY2FzZXMpLFxuICAgIGluY2lkZW50X2Nhc2VzID0gc3VtKGluY2lkZW50X2Nhc2VzKVxuICApXG5cbmNhX2NvbmZpcm1lZCAlPiVcbiAgZmlsdGVyKERhdGUgPj0gYXNfZGF0ZShcXDIwMjAtMDItMjdcXCkpICU+JVxuICBzZWxlY3QoRGF0ZSwgaW5jaWRlbnRfY2FzZXMpICU+JVxuICB1bmNvdW50KGluY2lkZW50X2Nhc2VzKSAtPiBjYV9pbmNpZGVuY2VcblxuY2FfaW5jaWRlbmNlX29iamVjdCA8LSBpbmNpZGVuY2UoY2FfaW5jaWRlbmNlJERhdGUsIGxhc3RfZGF0ZSA9IG1heChjYV9pbmNpZGVuY2UkRGF0ZSkpXG5cbmNhX2luY2lkZW5jZV9maXQgPC0gaW5jaWRlbmNlOjpmaXQoY2FfaW5jaWRlbmNlX29iamVjdClcbmNhX2luY2lkZW5jZV9maXRcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
ca_confirmed <- ca_confirmed_long_jhu %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  summarise(
    cumulative_cases = sum(cumulative_cases),
    incident_cases = sum(incident_cases)
  )

ca_confirmed %>%
  filter(Date >= as_date(\2020-02-27\)) %>%
  select(Date, incident_cases) %>%
  uncount(incident_cases) -> ca_incidence

ca_incidence_object <- incidence(ca_incidence$Date, last_date = max(ca_incidence$Date))

ca_incidence_fit <- incidence::fit(ca_incidence_object)
ca_incidence_fit

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

library(earlyR)
library(epitrix)
mu <- 7.5  # days
sigma <- 3.4  # days
param <- epitrix::gamma_mucv2shapescale(mu, sigma/mu)

w <- distcrete::distcrete(\gamma\, interval = 1, shape = param$shape, scale = param$scale, 
    w = 0)
R <- get_R(ca_incidence_object, si = w, si_mean=mu, sd=sigma)

library(projections)

pred_fwd_days <- 10

pred_growth <- project(ca_incidence_object, R = median(growth_R0), si=w, n_sim=10000, n_days = pred_fwd_days)

plot(ca_incidence_object) %>%
  add_projections(pred_growth) %>% 
  add_incidence_fit(ca_incidence_fit)
